node.text:
Where Dreams Are Born - Inspired by King Wisp by Bent⁠
⁠
Hi everyone! I am @camillehalluin and I’m a French artist, based in Ireland. By day I’m a digital designer and by night, a surreal artist. Let’s dive into my dreams and see what I #MadeWithPhotoshop⁠
⁠
Today I would like to invite you to travel within your imagination. Close your eyes and picture where you would like to go. Then suddenly, the walls around you disappear, the music starts playing and the place is right behind you.⁠
⁠
Whenever I listen to music, images come to my mind and this is what I pictured listening to King Wisp by Bent.⁠
⁠
Whenever we read a book, watch a movie, listen to a song, we plant our dream seeds, patiently waiting for them to bloom. Then, when the night comes and you fall asleep, you start traveling to places you had never imagined you would go.⁠
⁠
I sometimes wish the worlds I dream of could come true. Thanks to Photoshop I am able to capture them and bring magic into our lives.⁠
⁠
So hop on board and dream with me!⁠

Hello! It’s @weirdcreative. Photoshop has been an incredible tool in my career as a Visual Artist/Art Director, helping me bring what I envision to life. I’m excited to share with you what I #MadeWithPhotoshop ⁠
⁠
I had the idea to create a piece with a giant octopus in the ocean. I then further defined this concept with the rhyming of the words; tentacles and obstacles. I created this giant water cube as an obstacle for the octopus, with its tentacles breaking through. ⁠
⁠
I also wanted to convey the tone of calmness and security while in the midst of danger. I find that water and the color blue can be very calming elements.⁠
⁠
Hope this helps kick off some inspiration for you to create something in #Photoshop. I will be sharing tips and a breakdown of the process in the Stories! ⁠

Hello, this is @swissgo4design again. My work is all about perspectives. I make small things big, big things small, turn the horizon upside down, the sky into the sea, winter into the desert. #MadewithPhotoshop⁠
⁠
For my work, I usually use only two photos, like in this example. It is important that both photos have an identical horizontal line. Only then will the result look realistic and create a surprising effect when you look at it. ⁠
⁠
Then I adjust the colors, brightness, and saturation of both photos so that they blend into each other. ⁠
⁠
Smooth transitions work best with snow, sky, clouds, sand, smoke, or water because they have no clear boundaries. Identical colors can also make transitions easier, like in this photo where the sandy beach blends into the street.⁠
